News about Lionbridge Technologies Inc., including commentary and archival articles published in The New York Times.                    








Latest Articles







                    Business; Do You Speak Uzbek? Translators Are in Demand                
THE request arrived 12 days ago at Ad-Ex Translations Worldwide. A United States government agency -- Ad-Ex would not say which one -- asked the company to bid on a project to translate thousands of ordinary English words and phrases into Arabic, Dari, Pashto, Urdu and Uzbek. The proposal offered scant details, but the director of Ad-Ex, Robert L. Addis, thought he knew its purpose. The words to be translated were conversational, which seemed to rule out any technical, legal, financial or medical focus. And Pashto, Dari and Uzbek are spoken in Afghanistan, and the other languages are common in the region.











                    Technology Briefing | Software: Lernout Sells A Unit                
Lionbridge Technologies will buy the Mendez unit of Lernout & Hauspie, the troubled Belgian speech technology company, for $27 million in cash plus an additional $6 million to pay off Mendez debt. Mendez, a translation services and software provider, had been for sale for months as part of Lernout & Hauspie's bankruptcy restructuring. The unit, which is profitable, has about $80 million in annual revenue and was initially valued at $160 million, but the asking price was lowered repeatedly when few interested buyers appeared. Lionbridge, based in Waltham, Mass., provides multilingual content management systems. It said it would finance the purchase by selling preferred stock to institutional investors. The transaction, which is expected to be completed in the third quarter, is subject to approval by courts in the United States and Belgium. Jennifer 8. Lee (NYT)










COMPANY NEWS

                    LIONBRIDGE TO BUY INT'L.COM FOR $190 MILLION                
Lionbridge Technologies Inc. said yesterday that it had agreed to acquire Int'l.com, a rival provider of software conversion and Internet portal globalization services, for about $190 million in stock. Lionbridge, based in Waltham, Mass., and Int'l, based in Framingham, Mass., both help multinational companies convert software, translate help manuals and globalize Web sites for use by people in their native languages. Lionbridge and Int'l will have a combined work force of 900 employees in 10 countries. Lionbridge had sales of $38.4 million in 1998. Shares of Lionbridge rose $3.75 yesterday, to $25, in Nasdaq trading.











                    Offering by Lionbridge                
Lionbridge Technologies Inc. said yesterday that it had raised $35 million in the initial sale of the company's stock to the public. The 3.5 million shares sold for $10 apiece, their expected price. Shares of Lionbridge closed yesterday at $12.625 on volume of 10.8 million on the Nasdaq stock market. Based in Waltham, Mass., Lionbridge provides multilingual versions of its customers' software, hardware and other related material.



















Search Articles
4 results for  sorted by newest









                    Business; Do You Speak Uzbek? Translators Are in Demand                
THE request arrived 12 days ago at Ad-Ex Translations Worldwide. A United States government agency -- Ad-Ex would not say which one -- asked the company to bid on a project to translate thousands of ordinary English words and phrases into Arabic, Dari, Pashto, Urdu and Uzbek. The proposal offered scant details, but the director of Ad-Ex, Robert L. Addis, thought he knew its purpose. The words to be translated were conversational, which seemed to rule out any technical, legal, financial or medical focus. And Pashto, Dari and Uzbek are spoken in Afghanistan, and the other languages are common in the region.











                    Technology Briefing | Software: Lernout Sells A Unit                
Lionbridge Technologies will buy the Mendez unit of Lernout & Hauspie, the troubled Belgian speech technology company, for $27 million in cash plus an additional $6 million to pay off Mendez debt. Mendez, a translation services and software provider, had been for sale for months as part of Lernout & Hauspie's bankruptcy restructuring. The unit, which is profitable, has about $80 million in annual revenue and was initially valued at $160 million, but the asking price was lowered repeatedly when few interested buyers appeared. Lionbridge, based in Waltham, Mass., provides multilingual content management systems. It said it would finance the purchase by selling preferred stock to institutional investors. The transaction, which is expected to be completed in the third quarter, is subject to approval by courts in the United States and Belgium. Jennifer 8. Lee (NYT)










